                    <item>
              <title>Andy Brooks: Design Narrative, Reading for Gist</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/10325</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/10325</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<h2>Title</h2>
<h2>Design Narrative: To better enable English Language learners to read with an emphasis on reading for gist.</h2>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Narrator</h2>
<p>&nbsp;Student English Language Instructor at a language school.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Situation</h2>
<p>A language school offering English language lessons, this particular class was made up of young adults of intermediate ability English.</p>
<h2>Task</h2>
<p>Trying to improve reading skills but particularly to put an emphasis on reading for gist and to help improve reading speed.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Actions</h2>
<p>As a lead in the Students were shown a newspaper and an understanding of the body and headline and sub headline were checked. This was a simple activity which involved student participation.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Students were then put into pairs and asked to find a story they find interesting. They were given 3 minutes for this task. A check question was used to make sure the students understood the task, and duration.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Students then had to decide on two questions which were &ldquo;what is it about?&rdquo; and &ldquo;why is it interesting?&rdquo; Understanding of the task was checked using questions such as, &ldquo;Are you going to read every word?&rdquo; Students were given 3 minutes for this task. They were then asked about their stories.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Students were then given a couple of headlines to look at in their pairs and were asked what the stories could be about. After this Students were given a hand-out with some phrases and they had to decide which headlines they went with.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>As a final activity Students were given some stories and all around the level headlines had been hidden, they had to find the headlines and match them to the stories.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Results</h2>
<p>The lesson was a successful one and the students really enjoyed it, it was a fast paced lesson, but this led to the weaker students finding it quite difficult to keep pace, which was very noticeable at times. Overall the desired outcomes were achieved.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 27 Mar 2017 20:23:05 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Andy Brooks: H800 Healthy Eating design representations comparison</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/10324</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/10324</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>The 2 representations I chose are the 4 T's model and Web collage.</p>
<p><strong>Readability</strong></p>
<p>The 4 T's model is very readable and follows a linear path which I like, this makes it very user friendly and it is also very easy to see what at which point at a glance. Web collage could suit somebody who likes to visualise more and it is very flexible and can accomodate more complex information on one single representation.</p>
<p><strong>Expressiveness</strong></p>
<p>Both representations are expressive but the web collage lends itself more to expressionas it has the visual elements and allows the user to incorporate many different aspects in the single representation. This could work very well from the perspective of the healthy eating activity as it is spread over many weeks and the web collage represenntaion allows a complete overview. This is not to say the 4 T's lacks expression, but is a lot more simplistic in design.</p>
<p><strong>Utility</strong></p>
<p>Ease of use is the 4 T's strength as everything for that lesson can be seen at a glance and it is very easy to see what is happening, by whom and with what. The web collage is a lot more involved and less user friendly, but its strengths lay in other areas.</p>
<p>I chose the 2 above as they had good contrasting elements, I did, however, really like the e-design for both its simplicity and also the scaffolding features.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
