                    <item>
              <title>Review of 4T Model and Web Collage methods of Representation</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8692</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8692</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Review of 4 T&rsquo;s Model and Web Collage</strong></p>
<p>The 4T&rsquo;s model might have appealed to me because it appeared to come straight out of a project manager&rsquo;s handbook.&nbsp; The 4T&rsquo;s could be renamed to Task, People, Resources, Time or a variety of other titles that would also convey the same idea.</p>
<p>I liked the linear simplicity of this model, with its focus on constructivist pedagogies.&nbsp; The fact that each task is of a particular duration is an important factor in planning.&nbsp; The simple and elegant graphical illustration made the lesson plan easy to follow and understand, even when looking at collaborative group work in the class. I felt that it would be easy to use.</p>
<p>However, it was limited in that it did not have a focus on defining the environment, defining the objectives, or understanding the learner&rsquo;s aspirations.</p>
<p>Webcollage was the complete opposite of the 4Ts for me.&nbsp; I spent a not inconsiderable amount of time trying to comprehend it.&nbsp;&nbsp; I liked the idea that the model created could be used to create a lesson directly in moodle.&nbsp; I liked the idea of a collage of ideas, graphically represented, that could be quickly used to put together a raft of complementary activities in a lesson.&nbsp; But when taken as a whole, I felt that the method of modelling took something that should be simple, and made it into something more complex, the opposite of what it was supposed to achieve.</p>
<p>I found that I actually used items from 3 or 4 of the learning design representations when designing the learning activity that I described in Activity 1B.&nbsp; One of the keys to the success outlined in my chosen narrative was clearly defining the objectives and the environment.&nbsp; The other important aspect was not deviating from these, even when problems occurred. The overall design followed the path laid out in the eDesign Template representation, where the learner was first of all shown the important tasks, then she worked under supervision, and finally learned and worked on her own.&nbsp; However, the detail design followed the 4T&rsquo;s, with each Task given a resource in, an output and a time allocation.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 31 Mar 2014 18:58:17 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Paul McCullough&#39;s Design Narrative: Muddling through Moodle Management</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8690</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/8690</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Title</strong>&nbsp;Muddling through Moodle Management</p>
<p><strong>Narrator</strong></p>
<p>I design and setup elearning solutions for small healthcare agencies who want their staff to do compliance training online.&nbsp; The key to getting this setup to work is to make sure the Training Administrator (TA) who manages staff training, is confident in the use of the new system.&nbsp; If the TA understands and instructs her staff well, then I am not bothered by support calls.</p>
<p><strong>Situation</strong></p>
<p>The TA usually has had a the job of following protocols with regards training requirements &nbsp;and ensuring that training courses are organised and staff files are kept current.&nbsp;&nbsp; A new system of work can cause changes to the established way of working, and needs to be introduced with care.&nbsp; If the online training solution is seen to make everyone&rsquo;s lives easier and more manageable, then it is continued by management.&nbsp; If there is bad feedback from staff, then it is discontinued.</p>
<p>I have found that a training that follows specific protocols works well in these situations.&nbsp; I also have found that the training must take place with the candidate&rsquo;s own computer, so that they can take ownership of the training directly.</p>
<p><strong>Task</strong></p>
<p>If the client understands how to enrol students, what the common FAQ&rsquo;s are, and how to deal with common problems, then I do not get inundated with support queries.&nbsp; The measure of success is measured over the ensuing weeks, by the number of support calls I receive, and by the feedback the system receives from staff.</p>
<p><strong>Actions</strong></p>
<p>The first action was ensuring that the candidate&rsquo;s computer was setup in a way that ensured a successful &nbsp;outcome.</p>
<p>The company IT department had left IE7 as the default web browser.&nbsp; This is so out of date, that it wouldn&rsquo;t work with &nbsp;the HTML5 &nbsp;coursework that we use.&nbsp; I had to ask for an upgrade, and preferably for google chrome (which is automatically updated) to be installed.&nbsp;</p>
<p>The next stage was to set up a series of steps that the candidate could follow for each of the processes involved.</p>
<p>These included templates of instructions for enrolment, what to do when emails went missing, how to print out certificates and the basics of managing the site.</p>
<p>By having a folder with protocols set up, the training was reasonably simple and straightforward.</p>
<p>&nbsp;I also asked the TA to take notes that she could refer to in the future.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Results</strong></p>
<p>The results of the training were better than expected. By focusing on the client&rsquo;s desire to follow systems, I was able, in a short space of time, to get the online system rolled out to the agency&rsquo;s staff.</p>
<p>In the first week or so there were some minor hiccoughs, but things went relatively smoothly.</p>
<p>With my time not taken up doing support, I was able to offer some further courses to the company that they could use for staff development.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Both staff and management were very supportive of the system as both groups felt it gave them greater flexibility, while increasing interaction within the company.&nbsp; I felt that this was due, to a large degree, to the confidence that everyone had in using the system.&nbsp; This confidence was hinged on the clear instructions and support that they received at the start of their training by the TA.&nbsp; While the TA&rsquo;s attitude and personal competence played a major part, I would like to think that the training she received at the beginning, also helped in the success.</p>
<p><strong>Reflections</strong></p>
<p>Understanding that the TA wanted a series of protocols to follow, and providing these in a clear way, underpinned the success of this training.&nbsp; She was not interested in the the pedagogal and instructional theories that underpinned the training.&nbsp; The TA wanted to give clear instructions to candidates in what to do to complete the training, and wanted a simple outcome at the end of each training session.</p>
<p>Understanding&nbsp; the TA&rsquo;s objectives, and gearing the training to both her objectives, and her existing way of working, helped make the transition smooth.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 31 Mar 2014 14:43:19 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
