                    <item>
              <title>Lurkers as Learners</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3426</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3426</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Much evidence on the student use of collaborative tools such as online forums indicates that a majority tend to read them but not&nbsp;contribute. There is a gap therefore between how we design / anticpate their use and how they are used (unless students are compelled/forced to use them).&nbsp;&nbsp;How can we therefore best design for the behaviour&nbsp;of &lsquo;lurking&rsquo; (for want of a more enabling and positive term) and exploit it for learning?</p>
<p>&nbsp;Let&rsquo;s suppose that instead of relying on the &lsquo;possibly&rsquo; of someone in a particular group contributing something, why not &lsquo;fake&rsquo;, or rather let&rsquo;s say &lsquo;aggressively seed&rsquo;, the discussion forum? Why not prepare a set of useful real posts from previous years, add to this to posts written on behalf of &lsquo;imagined&rsquo; students and then intentionally drip feed them in to the forum at the appropriate time they were originally/intended to be made? You could call this &lsquo;time-shifted posting&rsquo; or &lsquo;simulated&rsquo; posting.</p>
<ul>
<li>Certainly what is 'collaborative' for one person is a broadcast or object purely for consumption by another. If the forum debate unfolds like a soap opera and most are only watching it, what would the difference really be?!</li>
<li>How do those reading forums &lsquo;know&rsquo; the people posting are real (in which case how does a student really &lsquo;know&rsquo; a post is from a &lsquo;real&rsquo; person unless they have met them face-to-face!)?</li>
<li>What is it these &lsquo;lurkers&rsquo; are getting from&nbsp;watching / reading things like online forums&nbsp;and discussion treads&nbsp;and are the patterns and content of posts currently 'on offer' or provided&nbsp;by them (by &lsquo;real&rsquo; people) really delivering what these &lsquo;lurkers&rsquo; want?</li>
</ul>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Mon, 26 Mar 2012 13:15:18 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Carrot or Stick? How to reach tipping point with a new technology in an institution.</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3387</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/3387</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>We are overwhelmed by new educational tools, but how do these become meaningful to our students? Reaching a tipping point when a technology becomes ubiquitous amongst students seems almost impossible, unless it's a tool as pervasive as google or email. So how do we get new tools out there? Should we push our Ss to use tools or else? Or should we just put stuff out there and see what sticks? Who has a success story here? And who feels that we are slowly sinking under the weight of all these new options?</p>]]></description>
